sec.p:
Test results for the DJIA index data are presented in panel A, and those for the S&P index data are in panel B.Table 1shows that index dividend (D), price (P), residual income (RI), adjusted price (
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $PB_{t}=P_{t}-B_{t}$ \end{document}
            ), and (modified) residual income series are all nonstationary, and their first differences are stationary for both the DJIA index data and the S&P index data. The spread for the DDM,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $S_{t}^{D},$ \end{document}
            appears to be nonstationary (i.e., dividends and stock prices are not cointegrated) for both the DJIA index data and the S&P index data. However, the spread for the RIM,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $S_{t}^{R},$ \end{document}
            appears to be stationary (i.e., the adjusted price and residual income are cointegrated) for both data sets (see Lamont1998). This finding suggests that, among other things, the deviation of stock prices from the DDM model (i.e., the intangible component of prices in the DDM model) is substantial (i.e., nonstationary), whereas the deviation from the RIM model is quite stable (i.e., stationary) (seeSection III.B). This finding also implies that the assumption of the RIM regarding the spread is more consistent with the data than that of the DDM.20

We are primarily interested in identifying the market's responses to tangible (i.e., public) and intangible (i.e., private) information (or shocks). Once we identify the two types of information (or shocks), as discussed inSection III, the coefficient of the identified moving average representation
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $c_{ij}^{k}$ \end{document}
               measures the effect of thejth shock, which could be either tangible or intangible, on theith variables inkperiods. To address the market's reactions over time, we plot the moving average coefficients,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $c_{ij}^{k},$ \end{document}
               over various horizons.21The overconfidence hypothesis anticipates that, in response to intangible shocks, stock prices will increase initially and then decrease over time.

Since we have derived restrictions that identify each type of innovation as either tangible or intangible, we can measure the relative importance of each innovation (or information) under these restrictions. Such a measure would be to use the fraction of forecast error variance in each variable explained by each type of disturbance. For example,

