The DJIA index data.Panel A oftable 2presents forecast error decompositions of the bivariate DDM model using the DJIA data for the sample period 1921–99. By construction, all variation in the first differenced dividends (ΔD) is explained by tangible shocks. When we compute forecast error variance for prices by expanding the spread (i.e.,
   \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $P_{t}=S_{t}^{D}+\theta D_{t}$ \end{document}
), intangible shocks are more important in short horizons but become less important as the horizon increases. Specifically, 26%, 34%, and 40% of 1‐year, 2‐year, and 3‐year‐ahead forecast error variances are explained by tangible (dividend) shocks, respectively, with the fraction increasing gradually to 88% as the forecast horizon increases. This indicates that prices tend to deviate from fundamentals (dividends) in short horizons, but the importance of dividends as tangibles increases in long horizons.

Panel B oftable 2presents forecast error decompositions of the bivariate RIM model. When we compute forecast error variance for prices by expanding the spread (i.e.,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $P_{t}=S_{t}^{R}+\mathrm{MRI}\,_{t}$ \end{document}
               ), intangible shocks are more important in short horizons but become less important as the horizon increases. Specifically, 28%, 38%, and 54% of 1‐year, 2‐years, and 3‐years‐ahead forecast error variances are explained by tangible (residual income) shocks, respectively, with the fraction increasing gradually to 95% as the forecast horizon increases. The comparison of the two bivariate models indicates that the tangibles in the RIM, residual income, explain marginally more of a fraction of price variation, implying that residual income may contain more useful information than dividends.

Panel C oftable 2presents forecast error decompositions of the trivariate model of the log‐linearized DDM model with a time‐varying interest rate. By construction, all variation in the first‐differenced log dividends (Δd) is explained by dividends’ own shocks. For the Δdr,dividend shocks dominate: about 71–82% of the variation is explained by dividend shocks, and the remaining 18–29% of the variation is explained by interest rate shocks. When we compute forecast error variance for log prices by expanding the spread (i.e.,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $p_{t}=s_{t}^{d}+d_{t}$ \end{document}
               ), intangible shocks explain more than half the variation in short horizons but lose their explanatory power as the time horizon increases. Dividend shocks explain between 36% and 75% of variation in log prices; interest rate shocks explain between 1% and 15% of variation in log prices, leaving 12–63% of variation in prices to be explained by intangible shocks, depending on forecasting horizons. Compared to the bivariate DDM model, the fraction of stock prices explained by tangibles is somewhat greater with the trivariate log‐linear model, which is an improvement with log‐linearization and time‐varying interest rates.

When we compute forecast error variance for log prices by expanding the spread (i.e.,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $p_{t}=s_{t}^{r}+x_{t+1}-ar_{t+1}1$ \end{document}
               ), intangible shocks explain about 39% of variation in the first year but lose their explanatory power as the time horizon increases. Specifically, 40%, 36%, and 31% of 2‐years, 3‐years, and 4‐years‐ahead forecast error variances in log prices are explained by intangible shocks, respectively, with the fraction decreasing gradually to 11% as the forecast horizon increases. Earnings shocks explain between 43% and 87% of variation in log prices; book‐value shocks explain between 1% and 19% of variation in log prices, depending on forecasting horizons. Compared to the bivariate RIM model, the fraction of stock prices explained by tangibles is greater with the trivariate log‐linear model, which is a significant improvement with a log‐linearization including earnings as a tangible variable. Compared to the trivariate log‐linear DDM model, the tangibles in the trivariate log‐linear RIM (i.e., earnings) explain a greater fraction of variation in log stock prices, which implies the superior performance of the RIM with earnings. The comparison also shows that earnings in the RIM model have stronger explanatory power than dividends in the DDM model for log stock prices.

Panel A oftable 3presents forecast error decompositions based on the bivariate DDM model using S&P index data. When we compute forecast error variance for prices by expanding the spread (i.e.,
                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $P_{t}=S_{t}^{D}+\theta D_{t}$ \end{document}
                  ), most of the variation in price is explained by intangible shocks. Specifically, only 3%, 4%, 7%, and 11% of 1‐year, 2‐years, 3‐years, and 4‐years‐ahead forecast error variances in prices are explained by tangible (dividend) shocks, respectively, and the fraction increases gradually to only 17% as the forecast horizon increases. This suggests that the bivariate DDM model does not capture the effect of tangible variables sufficiently and may be misspecified. Therefore, we do not place too much weight on the interpretation offigure 2(a), whose identification is based on the bivariate DDM model.

Panel B oftable 3presents forecast error decompositions based on the bivariate RIM model. When we compute forecast error variance for prices by expanding the spread (i.e.,
                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $P_{t}=S_{t}^{R}+\mathrm{MRI}\,_{t}$ \end{document}
                  ), intangible shocks dominate in short horizons but become less important as the horizon increases. Specifically, 11%, 27%, 47%, and 64% of 1‐year, 2‐years, 3‐years, and 4‐years‐ahead forecast error variances in prices are explained by tangible (residual income) shocks, respectively, and the fraction increases gradually to 94% as the forecast horizon increases. The comparison between the two bivariate models indicates that the tangible part of the RIM, residual income, explains substantially more variation than dividends. This implies that residual income may contain more useful information than dividends alone, and the RIM model may provide a better description of the price movements than the conventional DDM model. This indicates that, among other things, the deviation of stock prices from the simple DDM model is substantial. This finding casts doubt on the notion that changes in stock prices arise mainly from changes in market tangibles such as dividends, which is consistent with the rejection of the model by various variance bounds tests. Overall, these findings are very similar to those using the DJIA index data intable 2.

Panel C oftable 3presents forecast error decompositions for the trivariate model of the log‐linearized DDM model with a time‐varying interest rate. For the Δdr,about two‐thirds of the variation is explained by dividend shocks, while the remaining third of the variation is explained by interest rate shocks. This shows that dividends play a less important role than in the model using DJIA index data in panel C oftable 2. This may be in part because the DJIA companies are larger companies that pay dividends more regularly than companies in the S&P index. When we compute forecast error variance for log prices by expanding the spread (i.e.,
                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $p_{t}=s_{t}^{d}+d_{t}$ \end{document}
                  ), intangible shocks dominate in the short horizon (e.g., 82%) and lose their explanatory power gradually as the time horizon increases, down to 44%. Dividend shocks explain between 16% and 40% of variation in log prices, and interest‐rate shocks explain between 2% and 16% of variation in log prices, depending on forecasting horizons. This indicates that, as in the bivariate DDM model, the model does not capture the effect of tangible variables sufficiently and may be misspecified.23

Panel D oftable 3presents the forecast error decompositions for the trivariate model of the log‐linearized RIM model with a time‐varying return on equity (ar). For ROE, about 85–91% of variation is explained by earnings shocks, with the remaining 9–15% of variation explained by book‐value shocks, which implies that most of the variation in ROE is due to earnings changes rather than changes in book values. When we compute forecast error variance for log prices by expanding the spread (i.e.,
                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $p_{t}=s_{t}^{r}+x_{t+1}-ar_{t+1}$ \end{document}
                  ), intangible shocks explain more than half the variation in short horizons but lose their explanatory power as the time horizon increases. Specifically, earnings shocks explain between 5% and 76% of variation in log prices and book‐value shocks explain between 4% and 16% of variation in log prices, leaving between 20% and 80% of variation in prices to be explained by intangible shocks, depending on the forecasting horizon. Compared to the trivariate log‐linear DDM model, the tangibles in the trivariate log‐linear RIM explain a greater fraction of variation in log stock prices, which implies a superior performance by the RIM with earnings. The comparison also shows that earnings in the RIM model have substantially stronger explanatory power than dividends in the DDM model for log stock prices, which indicates that, among other things, the RIM tends to capture tangibles more effectively than the conventional DDM model.

